{
  "version": 1,
  "name": "Capacitor Charge Demo",
  "lesson": {
    "title": "Capacitor Charge Demo",
    "description": "USB → 470Ω → red LED → 1000µF capacitor → ground. When power is first applied, the empty cap draws charging current and the LED flashes bright, then fades over about 1–2 seconds as the cap fills (τ ≈ R×C ≈ 0.5 s). Once charged, DC current stops and the LED goes out — unlike a resistor, a capacitor stores energy instead of passing steady current forever. Orient the LED so conventional current flows anode (north) to cathode (south)."
  },
